<h1>LG Dryer Making Noise — What the Sound Tells Us and How We Fix It</h1>

<p>When your LG dryer starts making noise, the specific sound it makes is the most useful diagnostic information we have. Squeaking points to one set of parts. Grinding points to another. Thumping is different again. Before we even open the machine, a good description of the noise narrows it down to two or three possible causes — and in most cases we identify the exact problem within 15 minutes of arriving and show you the worn part before we replace anything. We handle noisy LG dryer calls constantly across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County, and the first question we always ask is: what exactly does it sound like?</p>

<h2>What Your LG Dryer's Noise Is Telling You</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Squeaking or Squealing
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Most common noise complaint</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">High-pitched, rhythmic</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Gets louder as dryer warms up</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Often worse when drum is loaded</div>
  </div>
  <p>Squeaking is almost always the drum rollers or the idler pulley — both wear items that fail after years of use. <strong>Drum rollers</strong> squeak when their rubber wears thin and the metal axle starts making contact. The sound is rhythmic and tied to drum rotation speed. It's often worse when the drum is loaded — the extra weight puts more pressure on the worn rollers. You can sometimes quiet it briefly by pressing lightly on the drum through the door. <strong>Idler pulley</strong> squeak is faster and more constant — tied to belt speed, which is higher than drum rotation. Often louder at the very start of a cycle. On DLGX and DLEX series after 3–5 years in Pasadena and Glendale we regularly find both need attention at the same time. Cost: drum rollers $280–350, idler pulley $200–260. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-drum-roller-replacement/">drum roller replacement</a> and <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-idler-pulley-replacement/">idler pulley replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Grinding or Rumbling
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Act on this one quickly</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Deep, constant — not rhythmic</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Metallic "groaning" sound</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Worse at start of cold cycle</div>
  </div>
  <p>Grinding or rumbling points to the drum bearing — the component at the rear of the drum that supports its weight. When the bearing wears out, the drum drags and you get that deep scraping sound under load. Customers in Beverly Hills and Torrance describe it as the dryer "groaning." Often constant rather than rhythmic, worse at the start of a cold cycle, then settling into a steady rumble once warmed up. This one is urgent — a worn bearing left running will score the drum surface itself, turning a $320 bearing repair into a $600+ bearing-plus-drum job. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-drum-bearing-replacement/">drum bearing replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Thumping or Banging
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Check for foreign objects first</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">One thump per drum rotation</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Hard object sound possible</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">May settle after warmup</div>
  </div>
  <p>Rhythmic thumping — once per drum rotation — usually means something hard is in the drum: a coin, button, or small tool lodged under a drum baffle (the raised fins inside the drum). Open the door, run your hand around the inside drum surface and under the baffles. A foreign object there produces a very consistent thump every rotation. Easy fix if that's what it is.</p>
  <p>If the drum is clear, thumping points to drum rollers that have developed a flat spot — a roller that sat idle developed a flat section that causes a thump every revolution until it warms up and rounds out. On some older machines the thump never fully goes away as the flat spot gets worse. Cost: $280–350 for roller replacement.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Rattling or Vibrating
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Often not a repair issue</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Loose, non-rhythmic sound</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">May come from outside the dryer</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Zippers, buckles, buttons in drum</div>
  </div>
  <p>Rattling is often not a dryer problem at all. Check the obvious things first: loose vent connection rattling against the wall, dryer feet not level causing vibration against the floor, items in pockets — zippers, buckles, buttons — rattling against the drum. If the rattle is clearly internal and nothing is in the drum, we check the drum baffles for looseness and the blower housing for debris. We've found small socks and lint buildup inside the blower housing on DLGX models in Irvine and Mission Viejo that caused rattling on every cycle.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Loud Bang at Startup
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Usually the belt</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Happens once at start</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Then runs normally</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Belt slapping the housing</div>
  </div>
  <p>A single loud bang or slap when the dryer first starts — then normal operation — is often the drive belt slapping the drum housing as it engages under load. Happens when the belt has stretched or when the idler pulley spring tension is weakening. Not dangerous, but it means the belt is working harder than it should and wearing faster than it should. Worth having us check the belt tension and pulley spring on the next visit.</p>
</div>

<h2>How to Describe the Noise When You Call</h2>
<p>The more specific you can be, the better prepared we'll be. Four things that help most when you call:</p>
<p><strong>Pitch:</strong> High-pitched squeak? Deep rumble? Medium grinding?</p>
<p><strong>Rhythm:</strong> Tied to drum rotation (slower rhythm)? Constant? Happens once per cycle at startup?</p>
<p><strong>Timing:</strong> Starts immediately? Gets worse as it warms up? Only when loaded?</p>
<p><strong>Location:</strong> Front of the machine? Back? Inside the drum or from the cabinet?</p>
<p>With that we can usually tell you on the phone whether it's rollers, bearing, pulley, or something else — and have the right parts on the truck before we arrive.</p>

<h2>Why Acting Early Saves Money</h2>
<p>Every noise failure has a cascade pattern. Squeaking rollers that get ignored eventually seize — the belt drags against them and wears out too. A grinding bearing left running scores the drum surface — now it's a bearing plus a drum replacement. An idler pulley that chirps for three months finally seizes and shreds the belt in one cycle. The noise is the dryer telling you something is wrong before it gets expensive. A $280 roller repair caught at the squeaking stage stays $280. The same machine three months later can be a $500+ job.</p>

