<h2>Questions We Get on These Calls</h2>

<h3>My LG dryer is squeaking — what's causing it?</h3>
<p>Almost always the drum rollers or idler pulley. Drum roller squeak is rhythmic and tied to drum rotation — often worse when the drum is loaded. Idler pulley squeak is faster and more constant. On machines 8+ years old we find both needing replacement at the same time more often than not. Describe the pitch and rhythm when you call and we can usually narrow it down before we arrive.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer is making a grinding noise — is it serious?</h3>
<p>Grinding means the drum bearing. Act on it quickly — a worn bearing left running will score the drum surface itself, turning a $320 repair into a $600+ bearing-plus-drum job. The longer the grinding goes on, the more damage accumulates.</p>

<h3>Should I continue using my dryer if it's making noise?</h3>
<p>Depends on the noise. Rattling from a loose vent connection: fine for now. Squeaking rollers or pulley: use it but get it looked at soon — every cycle accelerates the wear. Grinding bearing: stop using it. Metal-on-metal contact with the drum is happening and it gets worse every cycle.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer is thumping — is something stuck in it?</h3>
<p>Check the drum first — run your hand under the drum baffles (the raised fins inside the drum). A coin or button lodged there thumps exactly once per rotation. If the drum is clear, it's likely drum rollers with a flat spot. Either way, call us and we'll sort it out on the same visit.</p>

<h3>Do you use genuine LG parts for noise repairs?</h3>
<p>OEM only. Aftermarket drum rollers and pulleys use inferior bearing material and often fail in 12–18 months. We show you the part number and supplier cost when we're on-site — complete transparency before we start anything.</p>

